      "animation": "walk",
      "filename": "walk_000.png through walk_059.png",
      "source_sheet": "chatgpt_walk60_board_1_through_6",
      "note": "60-frame boxing shuffle-step walk cycle (1s at 60fps), replacing a prior 20-frame version that visibly 'tap-danced' (leg spread barely changed while the foot snapped abruptly between flat-on-ground and flexed-on-heel). Generated by ChatGPT as 6 sequential 10-panel boards, each board's first panel continuing exactly from the previous board's actual last panel (attached as a reference image extracted from that board's processed output, not a screenshot crop), covering the true mechanical sub-phases of a fixed-lead-foot shuffle: board1 front-foot heel-lift/toe-off, board2 front-foot airborne forward swing, board3 front-foot descent/landing/weight-transfer, board4 back-foot heel-lift/toe-off (mirrors board1), board5 back-foot airborne swing catching up (mirrors board2), board6 back-foot descent/landing/settle back to the board1-starting neutral guard pose (closing the loop). Front foot and back foot never swap. Board2's first attempt produced a static double-stance with no airborne leg and was discarded/regenerated using a bent-knee lifted-leg silhouette recovered from the pre-session git history walk_001.png as a corrective reference (leg silhouette only, ignoring that old reference's arms/back-leg/overall motion); the same reference was reused proactively for board5's mirrored motion, succeeding on the first try. Chroma-keyed and re-composited onto the standard 256x256 canvas using a per-board fixed scale factor chained via boundary bbox-height ratios (each board's scale = previous board's scale times the ratio of the previous board's last-frame height to this board's first-frame height), since even with continuity-reference chaining real scale drift occurs board-to-board. Board 6 additionally had real internal scale drift within its own 10 frames (its own source images split into two clusters, ~401px and ~346px bbox height, rather than a smooth pose-based variation) likely caused by also anchoring its ending to the absolute external walk_000 reference; corrected by linearly interpolating the target composited height itself (not the scale factor) from the board5/6 seam value to the walk_000 loop-closure value across board 6's 10 frames, then solving each frame's scale from its own raw bbox height. Feet stay at anchor y=214, centered at x=128.",
      "clipped": false
    },
